'Further, death by stoning constitutes torture or other cruel, degrading and inhumane acts of punishment, thus a clear infringement of international humanitarian principles and universal human rights.'

A Christian priest in Brunei said he was concerned by the development, but hoped the new system would be enforced less strictly than set down in the written law.

'They have been giving seminars to different groups to clarify,' said the priest, who declined to beidentified.

Authorities, he said 'seem genuinely concerned' at suggestions that the system would have an all-pervasive enforcement network.

Brunei's top Islamic scholar denied any suggestion the system would lead to extremes, persecution or cruelty.

'It is not indiscriminate cutting or stoning or caning', Awang Abdul Aziz was quoted as saying by statemedia after the law was announced.

'There are conditions and there are methods that are just and fair.'

